{"key":"post-9658210","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>9658210</id>\n<content>This method works for large amounts of straw, but you should have filled the PC at least 1/2 to 2/3 with water before starting, AND by soaking the straw first in HOT water, you already should have had it at 130F or so before you even started applying steam.&amp;nbsp; The straw should be on a rack, feed the steam in the bottom of the tote, and it will rise up and escape from the top.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;For smaller amounts, or for manure/coir type substrates, simply hydrate them to field capacity and put in quart jars, which can be placed in a large kettle of water and pasteurized that way right on the stove as demonstrated in the manure section on my DVD.&amp;nbsp; There's a sample clip on my website that demonstrates the process.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;If you boiled your PC dry, it's now junk so toss it.&amp;nbsp; However, if as I suspect it was a made in china model with a rubber gasket anyway, it was junk when you bought it.&amp;nbsp; Save up and get an AA now.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>9658716</next>\n<prev>9657814</prev>\n<first>9657437</first>\n<last>9659433</last>\n<when>1232648534</when>\n<utime>01/22/09 08:22 PM</utime>\n</post>"}